note.p: Mary Jane Clairmont was Godwin's second wife, whom he met in May 1801 and married at the end of that same year. Godwin's entries are at first to Mrs Clairmont, then Clairmont. He subsequently uses a mix of abbreviations and the full name before settling on Ct and Cts (when we assume either Charles or Jane is present). After their mariage references to Mary Jane become MJ, and are used, typically, only to refer to special events outside the house that they both attend, or instances of errands that he undertakes for her, or she for him. He also uses 'ditto' on a number of occasions as an abbreviation: for example, in 1805, there are many instances of 'Call with MJ on X; dine, ditto, at Y's'. The 'Cts' reference is also used in 1828/9 but on this occasion it appears to refer to Charles Clairmont and his family, and they have been coded accordingly.

There are six examples of MJ in 1797 and over fifteen in 1798 , but these probably refer to Magaret Jones, probably Louisa Jones's sister who may initially have played some role in the care of Fanny and Mary. After Louisa Jones leaves for Bath in 1798 here are no further entries for M Jones until 1801, suggesting that she may have accompanied her sister and returned home. References after 1801 are to M Jones, Margaret Jones, or some variation of the fuller name.
There are also a number of entries which read 'MJ + 4' - this is taken to mean Mary, Fanny, Charles, and Jane and to be coded as appropriate. For 'MJ + 5', add William Jnr.
